<TITLE> Bangladesh rises from 'worst 10' in TI index </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 17 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh, which had the tenth worse score last year in Transparency International's Corruption Perception Index, has emerged from the '10 worst' list this year. Transparency International Bangladesh executive director Iftekharuzzaman presented the TI's annual corruption report at a press conference in Dhaka Tuesday. The Berlin-based corruption watchdog released the report across the world the same day. The report said Bangladesh scored 2.4 on this year's index, coming 139th out of 180 countries, or 13th from the bottom. Pakistan, Belarus and Philippines scored the same. New Zealand scored 9.4, topping the list, while Somalia scored 1.1 coming last. Bangladesh ranked at the bottom of the list for five successive years from 2001-2005, perceived as the most corrupt country, according to the annual index. b
